  <p>Final-paycheck and late-pay rules are governed by state wage law, with substantial variation. The applicable rule depends on the state where the work was performed, whether the separation was voluntary or involuntary, the worker's classification (employee vs. independent contractor, exempt vs. non-exempt), the form of compensation owed (wages, bonus, commission, accrued vacation), and many other factors that a generic calculator cannot fully capture. Outcomes also depend on agency adjudication and judicial discretion. If you have an actual late-pay matter &mdash; whether you are a worker considering filing a claim or an employer assessing exposure &mdash; you should consult a licensed attorney in your jurisdiction before taking action.</p>

  <h2>2. Calculator Accuracy and Limitations</h2>
  <p>We make reasonable efforts to ensure the calculator's logic reflects mainstream state wage-law principles drawn from state labor codes, the published guidance of state-level wage enforcement agencies (California DLSE, NY DOL, Texas Workforce Commission, etc.), and leading state appellate decisions. However:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>State-by-state variation in final-paycheck deadlines is substantial. California requires payment on the date of involuntary termination (with the famous "waiting time penalties" if delayed); other states allow payment on the next regular pay date; some have no specific final-pay deadline.</li>
    <li>Penalty structures differ. California's waiting time penalties (Cal. Lab. Code &sect; 203) can amount to up to 30 days' wages per delayed final paycheck. Other states have lump-sum penalties, daily penalties capped at lower amounts, or no statutory penalty at all.</li>
    <li>The treatment of accrued-but-unused vacation, accrued PTO, and commissions/bonuses at separation varies by state. Some require payout; others don't.</li>
    <li>Independent-contractor classification disputes may need to be resolved before any late-pay analysis can be applied.</li>
    <li>Federal FLSA late-pay claims are a separate but related framework with their own remedies.</li>
  </ul>
